}}'''''Mi Tierra''''' ({{lang-en|'''''My Homeland'''''}}) is the third [[studio album]] by Cuban-American recording artist [[Gloria Estefan]], released on June 14, 1993 by [[Epic Records]]. Produced by husband [[Emilio Estefan]], it is her first Spanish-language album and pays homage to her Cuban roots. The album features Cuban musical genres, including boleros, ''danzan'' and ''son'' music. Recorded at Crescent Moon Studios in Miami, Florida, ''Mi Tierra'' features notable Latin musicians such as [[Arturo Sandoval]], [[Cachao L<U+00F3>pez]] and [[Paquito D'Rivera]].

The album was an international success, selling eight million copies worldwide as of 2006. In the United States it was the first record to reach number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart, and peaked at number twenty-seven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. ''Mi Tierra'' has sold over one million copies in the US and Spain. The album received favorable reviews from critics, who praised the album's production, songs and Estefan's vocals. Its success won the singer a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Tropical Latin Album|Best Tropical Latin Album]]. ''Mi Tierra'' spawned seven singles: "Mi Tierra", "Con Los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan", "Tradici<U+00F3>n", "Montuno", "<U+00A1>S<U+00ED> Se<U+00F1>or!...", "Mi Buen Amor" and "Ayer".

==Background==
Gloria Estefan had wanted to record a Spanish-language album reflecting her Cuban heritage since the beginning of her musical career.<ref name="q&a">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-06-22/entertainment/ca-5809_1_estefan-mi-tierra|title=Q&A With Gloria Estefan : 'Mi Tierra': Paying Tribute to Her Roots|last=Lopetegui|first=Ernesto|date=1993-06-22|accessdate=2013-01-14|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]}}</ref> Before recording in English, Estefan and her band performed at Latino nightclubs;<ref name="inspirations">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-06-24/features/9306240199_1_mi-tierra-miami-sound-machine-gloria-estefan|title=`Mi Tierra' Gloria Estefan Draws Inspiration From The Heritage Of Her Cuban Roots|last=Herrmann|first=Brenda|date=1993-06-24|accessdate=2013-01-14|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Company}}</ref>
she also remembered her grandmother teaching her old Cuban songs. Music had an important role in Estefan's family; her paternal grandmother was a poet, and an uncle played the flute in a salsa band.<ref name="q&a"/> The singer's desire to record an album in Spanish was also influenced by her son, Nayib; she wanted him to recognize his Cuban heritage.<ref name="inspirations"/>

==Recording and production==
''Mi Tierra'' was produced by Estefan's husband, [[Emilio Estefan]], and fellow Miami Sound Machine members Clay Ostwald and Jorge Casas.<ref name="Lannert"/> It features notable Latin musicians, including [[Nestor Torres]], [[Cachao L<U+00F3>pez]], Paquito Hechavarr<U+00ED>a, [[Paquito D'Rivera]], [[Arturo Sandoval]], [[Luis Enrique (singer)|Luis Enrique]] and [[Tito Puente]].<ref name="Morales">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Lpv25quOSnwC&pg=PA153&dq=gloria+estefan+mi+tierra+luis+enrique+cachao&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ipMiUpGpN9bBsAS214GoBw&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Latin Beat: The Rhythms And Roots Of Latin Music From Bossa Nova To Salsa And Beyond|last=Morales|first=Ed|page=153|publisher=De Capo|year=2003|isbn=9780786730209}}</ref> Additional performers include [[Sheila E.]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name="Morales"/><ref name="BLMAS"/> The album was recorded at Crescent Moon Studios in Miami, Floria.<ref name="Liner"/> [[Celia Cruz]] was invited to perform, but was unable to do so because of her touring schedule.<ref name="q&a"/> The album's cover features Estefan in a black-and-white photo at a Havana nightclub before the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PqIaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qSwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6719,6093610&dq=mi-tierra+gloria-estefan&hl=en|title=Gloria Estefan calls new album of Cuban music 'labor of love'|last=Shiner|page=106|first=Lo|date=1993-07-22|accessdate=2013-09-02|work=[[The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|publisher=[[Journal Communications]]}}</ref>

== {{anchor|Musical style and compositions}}Musical style and songs ==
{{Listen
|filename=Gloria Estefan - Con Los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan.ogg
|title=Gloria Estefan "Con los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan" (1993)
|description=A 27-second sample of "Con los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan" by Gloria Estefan, one of the album's bolero songs. In it, Estefan describes the years spent away from her lover.
|format=[[Ogg]]
|filename2=Gloria Estefan - Mi Tierra.ogg
|title2=Gloria Estefan "Mi Tierra" (1993)
|description2=A 27-second sample of "Mi Tierra", the lead single from the album. An uptempo song, it features Cuban salsa arrangements produced by Emilio Estefan.
|format2=[[Ogg]]
}}
The opening track on the album, "Con los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan" ("With the Years I Have Left"), is a Cuban [[bolero]] song. Three other bolero tracks on ''Mi Tierra'' are "Mi Buen Amor" ("My True Love"), "Volver<U+00E1>s" ("You'll Be Back"), and "Hablas de M<U+00ED>" ("You're Talking About Me").<ref name="Lannert"/><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZFyHfJ3MztwC&pg=PA53&dq=con+los+anos+me+quedan++gloria+estefan+boleros&hl=en&sa=X&ei=MSYkUtieOYjS9gTT74CQCQ&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=What a wonderful world (Qu<U+00E9> mundo tan maravilloso)|last=Alberola|first=Rafael|language=Spanish|page=53|year=2008|publisher=Editorial Club Universitario|isbn=9788484546474}}</ref> The title track details the passion of Estefan's homeland in a [[salsa music|salsa]] arrangement.<ref name="Lannert"/> In "Ayer" ("Yesterday") the singer finds a flower given to her by a lover and yearns for him to return, since life is short. Its music combines bolero and [[son (music)|son music]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BdBJ-pyBnJoC&pg=PT237&dq=gloria+estefan+ayer&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ti0kUonXFIvm8wTt2oDwAw&ved=0CE0Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Mujeres, espacio y poder|last=Fl<U+00F3>rez|first=Mercedes|language=Spanish|page=237|year=2006|publisher=ArCiBel Editores|isbn=9788493450823}}</ref> "No Hay Mal Que Por Bien No Bien" ("Out of All Bad, Some Good Things Come") is a [[danz<U+00F3>n]] recalling a brief love affair.<ref name="Lannert"/>

"<U+00A1>S<U+00ED> Se<U+00F1>or" ("Yes Sir!") is another ''son'' track featured on the album.<ref name="Morales"/> The bolero "Volver<U+00E1>s" was later covered by Mexican recording artist [[Alejandro Fern<U+00E1>ndez]] on his album ''[[Me Estoy Enamorando]]'' (1997), also produced by Emilio Estefan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/me-estoy-enamorando-mw0000029424|title=Me Estoy Enamorando&nbsp;<U+2014> Overview|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref> "Montuno" takes its name from the [[son montuno|musical genre of the same name]].<ref name="Gettelman"/> "Hablemos El Mismo Idioma" ("Let's Speak The Same Language") is an anthem, reaching out to other Latino groups, telling them that since they speak the same language they should leave their differences behind.<ref name="Allmusic"/> The album closes with "Tradici<U+00F3>n" ("Traditional"), which is performed as a [[guaguanc<U+00F3>]].<ref name="Lannert"/>

==Commercial reception==

===Album===
In the United States, ''Mi Tierra'' peaked at number twenty-seven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref name="us200"/> It was the first number-one album on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart, established when it was released.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CxAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=intitle:billboard+%22mi+tierra%22+%22argentina%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LiwcUrDqFNOK2QXW8IH4CQ&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Latin Notas|last=Lannert|first=John|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|page=26|date=1993-07-10|accessdate=2013-08-27}}</ref> The album spent a total of fifty-eight weeks atop the chart, until it was displaced by [[Selena]]'s album ''[[Amor Prohibido]]'' the week of June 11, 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Latin Albums &nbsp;<U+2014> Week of June 11, 1994|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1994-06-11/latin-albums |accessdate=2013-08-27|date=1994-06-11 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> It was more successful on the [[Tropical Albums|''Billboard'' Tropical Albums]] chart, where it spent ninety-one weeks on top.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Songs &nbsp;<U+2014> Week of April 1, 1995|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1995-04-01/tropical-songs |accessdate=2013-08-27|date=1995-04-01 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> ''Mi Tierra'' debuted at number one on the [[Latin Pop Albums|''Billboard'' Latin Pop Albums]] chart the week of June 11, 1993, but it was removed from the chart following week since it did not meet its criteria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latina Pop Albums &nbsp;<U+2014> Week of June 11, 1993|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/1993-07-10/latin-pop-albums |accessdate=2013-08-27|date=1993-06-11 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>

''Mi Tierra'' ended 1994 as the best-selling Latin album of the year in the United States.<ref name="usyearend"/> The album was certified 16&times; [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] by Latin standards, for shipments of 1.6 million copies in the U.S.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|title=Mi Tierra|artist=Gloria Estefan|type=album|award=Platinum|number=16|Spanish=yes|accessdate=2012-05-24}} According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], it sold 1,198,000 copies in the U.S. by 2007; according to ''Billboard'', most purchasers did not speak Spanish.<ref name="ussales"/> In Latin America, the album was certified double platinum in Argentina and triple platinum in Mexico.<ref name="argcert"/>{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Mexico|title=Mi Tierra Combatir|artist=Gloria Estefan|type=album|award=Platinum|number=3|relyear=1993|certyear=2000|accessdate=2011-04-05}} It sold over 30,000 copies in Chile.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA70&dq=intitle:billboard+%22mi+tierra%22+%22argentina%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LiwcUrDqFNOK2QXW8IH4CQ&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Record Biz Tries To Warm A Chilly Market|last=Lannert|first=John|volume=106|issue=50|page=70|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=1994-12-10|accessdate=2013-08-27}}</ref>

In Europe, ''Mi Tierra'' peaked at number fifty-nine in Germany,<ref name="germancharts"/> number nine in the Netherlands,<ref name="dutchcharts"/> number one in Spain,<ref name="spanishcharts"/> number twenty-five in Switzerland and number eleven in the United Kingdom.<ref name="swisscharts"/> The album was certified 10&times; platinum in Spain (for shipping one million copies) and certified gold in Switzerland.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Switzerland|title=Mi Tierra|artist=Gloria Estefan|type=album|award=Gold|relyear=1993|accessdate=2011-04-05}}{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Spain|title=Mi Tierra|artist=Gloria Estefan|type=album|award=Platinum|number=10|relyear=1993|id=04_23|accessdate=2011-04-05}} ''Mi Tierra'' was the 60th-best-selling album of the 1990s,<ref>{{cite book|last=Dodd|first=Peter|title=100 best selling albums of the 90s|page=13|publisher=Amber Books|year=2004|isbn=9781904687139}}</ref> and sold over eight million copies worldwide by 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keyt.com/entertainment/4383616.html|title=Essential Gloria Estefan: First 2-CD Collection to Span Career|last=Daniel|first=Susanna|date=2006-07-23|accessdate=2013-01-14|work=KEYT-TV|publisher=[[News-Press & Gazette Company]]}}</ref>

===Singles===
"Mi Tierra" was the first single released from the album. In the United States, it reached number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs]] chart and number five on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mi Tierra&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/song/gloria-estefan/mi-tierra/1915467|accessdate=2012-06-02 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> In Europe, the song peaked at number seventy-seven on the [[Media Control]] charts in Germany, twenty-seventh on the [[Mega Single Top 100]] chart in Netherlands and thirty-sixth on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mi Tierra&, Gloria Estefan|url=http://www.charts.de/song.asp?artist=Gloria+Estefan&title=Mi+tierra&country=de|accessdate=2012-06-02|language=German|work=Media Control|publisher=PhonoNet GmbH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutchcharts.nl&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan&nbsp;<U+2014> Mi Tierra|url=http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Gloria+Estefan&titel=Mi+Tierra&cat=s|language=Dutch|accessdate=2012-06-02|publisher=Mega Single Top 100. Hung Medien / hitparade.ch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Archive Chart|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1993-07-03/|accessdate=2012-06-02|publisher=[[UK Singles Chart]]. Official Charts Company.}}</ref> The second single, "Con Los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Quedan", also reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Con Los A<U+00F1>os Que Me Queden&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/song/gloria-estefan/con-los-anos-que-me-quedan/371984|accessdate=2012-06-02 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> An English version, "If We Were Lovers", was released as a single and peaked at number forty on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archive Chart|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1993-08-14/|accessdate=2012-06-02|publisher=[[UK Singles Chart]]. Official Charts Company.}}</ref> The third single, "Tradici<U+00F3>n", reached number one the Hot Dance Clubs chart in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tradici<U+00F3>n&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/song/gloria-estefan/tradicion/371995|accessdate=2012-06-02 |work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref>

"Montuno" was the fourth single released from the album, peaking at number fifty-five on the UK Singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Official Charts Company;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan&nbsp;<U+2014> Montuno|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/search-results-album/_/Montuno#single|accessdate=2012-06-02|publisher=Official Charts Company}}</ref> The fifth single, "<U+00A1>S<U+00ED> Se<U+00F1>or!..." peaked at number forty-four on the Mega Single Top 100 chart in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dutchcharts.nl&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan&nbsp;<U+2014> <U+00A1>S<U+00ED> Se<U+00F1>or!...|url=http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Gloria+Estefan&titel=%A1Si+se%F1or%21%2E%2E%2E&cat=s|language=Dutch|accessdate=2012-06-02|publisher=Mega Single Top 100. Hung Medien / hitparade.ch}}</ref> The sixth, "Mi Buen Amor", reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs chart in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mi Buen Amor&nbsp;<U+2014> Gloria Estefan|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/song/gloria-estefan/mi-buen-amor/1963104|accessdate=2012-06-02 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The last single released from the album was "Ayer", which peaked at number five on the Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gloria Estefan Album & Song Chart History|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/gloria-estefan/chart-history/4564?f=363&g=Singles|accessdate=2012-06-02 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>

==Critical reception and accolades==
{{Album reviews
|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]
|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Allmusic">{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/m%C3%AD-tierra-mw0000098094|title=Mi Tierra&nbsp;<U+2014> Review|first=Jose|last=Promis|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref>
|rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''
|rev2score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name="Obejas">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-09-23/features/9309230104_1_mi-tierra-miami-sound-machine-star|title=Tempo Recordings|last=Obejas|first=Achy|date=1993-09-23|accessdate=2012-05-24|work=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Company}}</ref>
|rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''
|rev3Score = favorable<ref name="Hurley">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,307054,00.html|title=Mi Tierra Review|last=Hurley|first=Anne|date=1993-06-25|accessdate=2012-06-24|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]}}</ref>
|rev4 = ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''
|rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Gettelman">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1993-07-09/entertainment/9307070722_1_estefan-mi-tierra-gloria|title=Gloria Estefan|last=Gettelman|first=Peter|date=1993-07-09|accessdate=2013-01-14|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publisher=Tribune Company}}</ref>
|rev5 = ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]''
|rev5score = favorable<ref name="Lannert">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-06-20/features/9301190734_1_mi-tierra-english-language-percussion-and-bass|title=Disc Satisfying, Convincing|last=Lannert|first=John|date=1993-06-20|accessdate=2013-01-14|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|publisher=Tribune Company}}</ref>
}}

Jose F. Promis of [[Allmusic]] awarded the album four stars out of five, calling it "one of [Estefan's] most satisfying."<ref name="Allmusic"/> ''Mi Tierra'' was "a breezy, sunny album with moments of melancholy," and "one of her most consistent albums to date."<ref name="Allmusic"/> [[Achy Obejas]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the album four out of four stars, praised it as "dispensing with the brash sound of more contemporary salsa" and lauded Emilio Estefan for the album's production.<ref name="Obejas"/> Anne Hurley of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said that ''Mi Tierra'' "will whirl you through an intoxicating landscape of traditional Cuban rhythms and aromatic flavors," and applauded the guest musicians on the album.<ref name="Hurley"/>

Parry Gettelman of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave ''Mi Tierra'' four out of five stars, commending the album as "uncompromising, offering up songs and arrangements firmly rooted in Cuban traditions."<ref name="Gettelman"/> He compared it to Estefan's earlier recordings with the Miami Sound Machine, including her musical style and songwriting: "She ditches the synths and employs the London Symphony Orchestra's strings to graceful effect...abandoning melodrama for real color and emotional shading."<ref name="Gettelman"/> John Lannert described ''Mi Tierra'' for the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' as "Estefan`s Latin 'unplugged' album" and her "most satisfying effort to date."<ref name="Lannert"/>

At the [[1994 Grammy Awards|36th Grammy Awards]], ''Mi Tierra'' was the [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Tropical Latin Album|Best Tropical Latin Album]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-03-02/entertainment/ca-29147_1_grammy-awards|title=The 36th Annual Grammy Awards : And the Grammy Goes to . . . Winners According to Category|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=1994-03-02|accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> At the [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1994|6th Lo Nuestro Awards]] Estefan received two awards in the tropical category, for Female Artist of the Year and Album of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=490961|title=Lo Nuestro 1994 &nbsp;<U+2014> Historia de Premio lo Nuestro|language=Spanish|year=1994|accessdate=2011-10-03|work=[[Univision]]|publisher=[[Univision Communications]]}}</ref> The singer was Female Artist of the Year at the first [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], and ''Mi Tierra'' was Album of the Year in the tropical-salsa category.<ref name="BLMAS">{{cite journal| last = Lannert| first = John| date = 1994-05-21| title = First Latin Music Awards Recognize Range of Talent| work = Billboard| publisher = Prometheus Global Media| volume = 106| issue = 32| page = LM-52| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=TAgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=marc+anthony+%22otra+nota%22+intitle:billboard&hl=en&ei=BmKJTs-8BMKctwf5xtGpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate = 2010-06-03}}</ref> At the 1994 Spanish [[Premios Ondas|Ondas Awards]], ''Mi Tierra'' was the Best International Album and Estefan the Best International Artist. It was recognized as the best-selling Latin album of the year with a 1993<U+2013>94 NARM Best Seller Award.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=QQgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42&dq=intitle:billboard+%22mi+tierra%22+%22gloria%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TcK9T9H4L9DmggeX3eSpDw&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Estefan Tops 'Un A<U+00F1>o De Rock'|last=Llewellyn|first=Howard|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|volume=106|issue=15|pages=42, 47|date=1994-04-09|accessdate=2013-09-02}}</ref>

